  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Sports for Health: supporting employemnt opportunities for disabled youth</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Disabled children and young people growing up in Kenyan slums can face significant difficulties and challenges, including a lack of education and being stigmatised because of their disability. AbleChildAfrica runs sports programmes for disabled people, helping them to develop self-confidence and preparing them to find work. Over the course of a year, those affected participate in professionally coached sporting opportunities and an intensive course of business training and work placements. The project provides lifelong opportunities for disabled people, helping them to achieve their full potential and fully participate in the world around them. It also helps to change attitudes to disability throughout Kenyan society. In addition to the project grant, AbleChildAfrica has been awarded &#xA3;40,000 to help strengthen the organisation and their work, enabling them to support their local partners in Africa to continue to provide effective solutions to the issues they address.</narrative>
  </description>
